Package net.xqhs.flash.core.util

Class MultiTreeMap

  • java.lang.Object
    • net.xqhs.util.config.Config
      • net.xqhs.flash.core.util.MultiValueMap
        • net.xqhs.flash.core.util.MultiTreeMap
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, net.xqhs.util.config.Configurable
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    DeploymentConfiguration
    public class MultiTreeMap
extends MultiValueMap
    The class acts as a tree of key-value pairs that allows multiple values for the same key. Keys are also called names.

    The class builds on the same principles as MultiValueMap but acts rather like a hierarchical MultiValueMap. It has two types of names.

    • Some names are "simple", in that they act exactly like names with String values in a MultiValueMap. There is a name and one or more String values associated with the name.
    • Other names are "hierarchical" (or tree-keys). Each hierarchical name has one or more associated MultiTreeMap values.

    The class extends MultiValueMap such that only the two types of values are admitted -- String and MultiTreeMap. One name can be associated wither with String values, or with tree values, but not with a combination thereof (a name must either be simple or hierarchical).

    There is no intersection allowed between the set of names for simple values and the set of types for tree values.

    For clearer implementation and easier debugging, there are separate methods for the names which are supposed to only hold one value (call them singleton names), both for simple and for tree names. It is possible to change the singleton status of names by calling makeSingleton(java.lang.String, boolean).

      • addItem

        protected MultiTreeMap addItem​(java.lang.String name,
                               java.lang.Object value,
                               boolean isSimple,
                               boolean isSingleton,
                               boolean isFirst)
        Internal method for associating a value with a name. The value can be simple or a tree, and it can be singleton or not.

        If the name is not pre-existing, it is added accordingly.

        Exceptions are thrown if

        • The name has been added as singleton but now the new value is added as an additional value.
        • The name has been added as a non-singleton value but the new value is added as a singleton value.
        • The name is simple, but the value is a tree; or the name is hierarchical, but the value is a string.

        If the name is existing and singleton, the given value replaces the existing association.

        Parameters:
        name - - the name (key) of the entry.
        value - - the value, either a String or a MultiTreeMap instance.
        isSimple - - true if the name is expected to be simple, false if it is expected to be hierarchical.
        isSingleton - - true if the name is associated with a singleton value, false if multiple values can be associated with the name.
        isFirst - - true if the value should be added as the first value to be associated with the name; false if as the last.
        Returns:
        the instance itself.

      • getCreateTree

        protected MultiTreeMap getCreateTree​(java.lang.String name,
                                     boolean create,
                                     boolean isSingletonName)
        Retrieves the first tree associated with the given name.

        Optionally, if no such tree exists, creates one, adds it as a value for the given name and returns it.

        Parameters:
        name - - the name (key) to search.
        create - - if true and no tree is associated with the name, a new tree is added for the given name and returned. If false, the method is the same as getSingleTree(String) or getFirstTree(String), depending on the value of the last argument.
        isSingletonName - - if the previous argument is true, this arguments indicates whether the newly created name should be created as a singleton name (this argument should be true) or not (this argument should be false). If the previous argument is false, this indicates whether the name should be considered as singleton or not.
        Returns:
        the first associated tree.

      • copyNameFrom

        public MultiTreeMap copyNameFrom​(MultiTreeMap from,
                                 java.lang.String name)
        Adds to this tree the contents associated with the specified name in the from tree, with exactly the same type of key (singleton / hierarchical).

        If the key already exists, is singleton and is hierarchical, the individual trees are recursively copied into the key (the tree associated with the singleton key is merged).

        For singleton simple names, warnings should be issued (but currently are not) on overwrite but currently are not.

        WARNING: nothing is copied, except for the actual reference; associated with the name there will be exactly the same instances as in the other MultiTreeMap (except for singleton hierarchical keys, which are merged).

        Parameters:
        from - - the source MultiTreeMap
        name - - the name (key) to transfer
        Returns:
        the instance itself

      • copyNameFromDeep

        public MultiTreeMap copyNameFromDeep​(MultiTreeMap from,
                                     java.lang.String name)
        Adds to this tree the contents associated with the specified name in the from tree, with exactly the same type of key (singleton / hierarchical).

        If the key already exists, is singleton and is hierarchical, the individual trees are recursively copied into the key (the tree associated with the singleton key is merged).

        For singleton simple names, warnings should be issued (but currently are not) on overwrite but currently are not.

        In this version of the method, trees are copied with copyDeep(), so that in the end disjoint trees exist in the to MultiTreeMap instances for the given key.

        Parameters:
        from - - the source MultiTreeMap
        name - - the name (key) to transfer
        Returns:
        the instance itself

      • copyShallow

        public MultiTreeMap copyShallow()
        Creates a shallow copy of this MultiTreeMap, by creating a new instance with the same parings (an identical backing map) and in the same order as the original; new, identical lists are created for the simple keys, the tree keys, and the singleton keys.

        NOTE THAT the values are the same in both maps. That is, both maps have references to the same instances for values.

        Returns:
        the shallow copy of this map.

      • copyDeep

        public MultiTreeMap copyDeep()
        Creates a deep copy of this MultiTreeMap, by creating a new instance with the same parings and in the same order as the original; new, identical lists are created for the simple keys, the tree keys, and the singleton keys. The method recurses through the trees that this instance contains.
        Returns:
        the shallow copy of this map.

      • getDeepValue

        public java.lang.String getDeepValue​(java.lang.String... names)
        Get the value at the end of a path in a tree. The last name must be a simple name. All other names must be hierarchical names. For multiple values, only the first value is checked.

        The method fails fast: if one of the names (except for the last one) is not a hierarchical name, the method returns null.

        Parameters:
        names - - the path, consisting of names.
        Returns:
        the value associated with the leaf at the end of the path, if any is found; null otherwise.
